The reflection matrix is given by $R = Q\;\text{diag}(1, -1)\,Q^t, $ where $Q$ is the orthonormal matrix with columns $u_1, \ldots, u_k$, and $e_1, \ldots, e_k$ are idempotent vectors satisfying $Qe_i = u_i$.  (This can be verified by observing that $Rv_i = v_i$ for any idempotent vector $v$.)    </think>
The first thing to realize is that the vectors we are reflecting the basis on to the reflection should be the eigenvectors of that reflection.
So we need to find the eigenvectors corresponding to $-1$. If I call $u_1$ the first eigenvector and $[1,0]^t$ the second eigenvector, I see that they satisfy :
\begin{eqnarray}
\begin{pmatrix}
  a & b \\
  c & d
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}
  1 \\ 0
\end{pmatrix} &=& -1\begin{pmatrix}
  1 \\ 0
\end{pmatrix}\\
\begin{pmatrix}
  a & b \\
  c & d
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}
  3 \\ 2
\end{pmatrix} &=& -1\begin{pmatrix}
  3 \\ 2
\end{pmatrix}
\end{eqnarray}
$i.e.,$ $\begin{cases}
  a = -1 \\
  \text{ and } \ \begin{cases}
    a = -3 \\
    2c = -6.
  \end{cases}\\
  \text{ and }\begin{cases}
  3c + 2b = -3\\
  3d + 2b = -2
  \end{cases}.
\end{cases}$
Thus $a = -1, \; b = -3/2, c = -3, \; d = - 1/2$. So the reflection matrix is :
$$\begin{pmatrix}
  -1 & -3/2 \\
  -3 & -1/2 
\end{pmatrix}.$$

